### Example 3: Hardened `ObjectMapper` configuration (defense in depth)

Raw validation is the primary control. After it passes, harden databind.

```java
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.*;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.jsontype.BasicPolymorphicTypeValidator;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.core.json.JsonReadFeature;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.core.JsonFactory;

public final class HardenedMapperFactory {

  public static ObjectMapper create() {
    JsonFactory jsonFactory = JsonFactory.builder()
        .enable(JsonReadFeature.STRICT_DUPLICATE_DETECTION) // extra safety
        .build();

    ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper(jsonFactory);

    // Prefer failing on unknown properties for sensitive endpoints (depends on compatibility needs)
    mapper.enable(DeserializationFeature.FAIL_ON_UNKNOWN_PROPERTIES);

    // Ensure default typing is NOT enabled unless you absolutely need it
    // (Do NOT call enableDefaultTyping on modern Jackson.)

    // If you must support polymorphic types, allowlist:
    PolymorphicTypeValidator ptv = BasicPolymorphicTypeValidator.builder()
        .allowIfSubType("com.mycompany.safe.types")
        .build();
    // mapper.activateDefaultTyping(ptv, ObjectMapper.DefaultTyping.NON_FINAL); // only if required

    return mapper;
  }
}
```

Guidance:
- If your endpoint can be modeled without polymorphism, do so.
- Avoid binding to `Object` / `Map<String,Object>` for high-risk endpoints; POJOs constrain what can appear.

